org.incava.ijdk.collect

Class BaseArray<T,C extends BaseArray<T,C>>

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.util.AbstractCollection<E>
      • java.util.AbstractList<E>
        • java.util.ArrayList<T>
          • org.incava.ijdk.collect.BaseArray<T,C>
  • Type Parameters:
    T - the element type of the array
    C - the class of the array subtype
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Cloneable, java.lang.Iterable<T>, java.util.Collection<T>, java.util.List<T>, java.util.RandomAccess, Sequence<T,C>
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    Array, IntegerList, StringList

    public abstract class BaseArray<T,C extends BaseArray<T,C>>
extends java.util.ArrayList<T>
implements Sequence<T,C>
    A dynamically-sized collection, wrapping ArrayList. Array, a subclass of BaseArray, has a simpler name. To subclass this, the subclass should pass its class as a self type. For example: 
        public class StringList extends BaseArray<String, StringList>
    See Also:
    Serialized Form

      • get

        public T get(int index)
        Returns the nth element in the list.

        Unlike java.util.ArrayList#get, org.incavaijdk.collect.Array#get supports negative indices, as do languages such as Perl and Ruby.

        If n is negative, then the index is the offset from the end, where -1 is the last element, -2 is the second to last element, and so on and so forth. If n is out of range (not within 0 ... size()), then null is returned.

        Specified by:
        get in interface java.util.List<T>
        Overrides:
        get in class java.util.ArrayList<T>
        Parameters:
        index - the index into this array
        Returns:
        the element at the given index, or null if invalid

      • get

        public C get(int fromIndex,
             int toIndex)
        Returns an array (of the generic subtype) containing the mth element through the nth element in the list, both inclusive.

        If m n is negative, then the index is the offset from the end, where -1 is the last element, -2 is the second to last element, and so on and so forth. If m or n is out of range (not within 0 ... size()), then an empty set is returned.

        Parameters:
        fromIndex - the beginning index into this array, inclusive
        toIndex - the ending index into this array, inclusive
        Returns:
        the element at the given index, or null if invalid

      • set

        public T set(int index,
             T value)
        Sets the nth element in the list.

        If n is negative, then the index is the offset from the end, where -1 is the last element, -2 is the second to last element. Unlike ArrayList#set, this method honors the dynamically sized aspect of the list, and resizes it accordingly when set(index, obj) && index > size(). However, set(-index, obj) (a negative index value) will result in an IllegalArgumentException when -index > -size().

        Specified by:
        set in interface java.util.List<T>
        Overrides:
        set in class java.util.ArrayList<T>
        Parameters:
        index - the index at which to set the element
        value - the value to set
        Returns:
        the old value, or null if none

      • elements

        public C elements(int... indices)
        Returns a list of the elements at the given indices. As with get, negative indices are treated as offsets from the last element. 
             Array<Integer> list = Array.of(6, 7, 8);
     Array<Integer> l2 = list.elements(0);         // [ 6 ]
     Array<Integer> l3 = list.elements(0, 1);      // [ 6, 7 ]
     Array<Integer> l4 = list.elements(1, 0);      // [ 7, 6 ]
     Array<Integer> l5 = list.elements(-1, -2, 1); // [ 8, 7, 7 ]
        Parameters:
        indices - the indices to get
        Returns:
        a new array, containing the elements for the indices
        See Also:
        get(int)
